The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Live your dream: Leander
                                                                                                                       7                                      Live your dream: Leander
            A STAFF REPORTER                      
	Calcutta: The Gorky Sadan auditorium was overflowing long before he had arrived. Chief guest Leander Paes didnt disappoint the youngsters  and a few kids too  at The Telegraph Schools Chess Championship prize distribution on Monday evening, encouraging and inspiring them to live a dream.         
	Looking dapper in a dark blue pin-striped suit, the 12-time Grand Slam winner said: With a little bit of self belief and lots of hard work it is possible to realise any dream, he said.         
	If you have the courage and the passion, you can be the next Sachin Tendulkar or Viswanathan Anand. Coming from this city I was able to live a dream and was passionate about it A dream to win a Grand Slam, a Davis Cup         
	His words were like music to the talented youngsters.         
	From champion Sayantan Das to four-and-half-year old Ritiwika Ghosh, the youngest participant in the tournament, Paes smilingly met the demands of autographs and photographs.         
	He also didnt forget to mention his roots. Wherever Ive played, Ive been holding the West Bengal flag high My mom is a Bengali and Im proud to be a Bengali Ami Bangla bolte pari, bujhte pari But that is for another day.         
	Monday was only about showing the way. Live your dream to be a Grandmaster or a world champion If you dare to dream, everything is possible In years to come, Im sure some talent will emerge from here as the next world champion, Paes stressed.         
	I started playing tennis at the age of five and left home at 12 I dreamt about winning in Wimbledon one day and made it possible         
	Paes also congratulated Sachin Tendulkar on his 50th century.         
	A phenomenal achievement. Its fantastic An awesome feat. He is really God-gifted. I really respect the longevity of his performance Nobody expected Sunil Gavaskars record of 34 Test hundreds to be broken Sachin has not only got past him but also set new standards, Paes said.                                                                                                                     
